December 12, 2022 Commentary
The clear, correct, and error-free coefficients of this RK pair can be found in
Jacob Williams' Fortran Astrodynamics Toolkit. The coefficients are difficult to read out
from the paper because of the many almost faded out numbers. I managed to correctly 
type out all of them except the a[11,7] entry. I read it out as 
0.114488 9 5006396106323658875721817, rather than 0.114488 0 5006396105323658875721817.

As a result, the coefficients in the a[11] row sum up to 0.891000 9 0000000001, instead of just 0.891.
I didn't detect it months ago because I would compare the c[i] entries and row sums of a[i] using 
numpy's isclose function with the default rtol and atol tolerances of 1e-5 and 1e-8, respectively.
Using more strict tolerances of 1e-12 and 1e-12 revealed the error.

The error is at the 7th digit from the decimal place. This resulted in the accuracy of my implementations
always being capped at 1e-5 to 1e-6. I couldn't figure out where my error was when I coded this RK pair
months ago and I simply gave up. Now, months later, I thought of "fixing" the coefficient with the smallest
magnitude in the a[11] row which is the a[11,7]-th entry. This "fix" worked I managed to have my the Fehlberg
pair achieve very accurate results!

Just to be sure, I remembered and compared this to Jacob William's implementation of the coefficients,
specifically the a[11,7]-th entry, and I found that I "fixed" the right coefficient, and not any of the others!

To summarize:
my wrong interpretation : 0.114488 9 5006396106 323658875721817
my "fix"                : 0.114488 0 5006396106 744744347242017
the right one           : 0.114488 0 5006396106 323658875721817
